
00:00:03,708 --> 00:00:07,382
NARRATOR:
  This is the Shark Tank,

00:00:07,382 --> 00:00:09,051
where hopeful entrepreneurs

00:00:09,051 --> 00:00:11,790
get a once-in-a-lifetime chance
  to pitch the sharks

00:00:11,790 --> 00:00:13,461
in hopes
  of getting an investment

00:00:13,461 --> 00:00:16,400
to start, grow,
  or save their businesses.

00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:18,804
I'm asking for $150,000...

00:00:18,804 --> 00:00:20,375
...For 30% of my company.

00:00:20,375 --> 00:00:22,212
NARRATOR: The entrepreneurs
  must convince a shark

00:00:22,212 --> 00:00:24,316
to invest the full amount
  they're asking for,

00:00:24,316 --> 00:00:26,587
or they'll walk away
  with nothing.

00:00:26,587 --> 00:00:28,324
Someone wants
  to come after my business

00:00:28,324 --> 00:00:30,996
and take the food out of
  my kids' mouths, I will fight!

00:00:30,996 --> 00:00:33,835
I started this company
  'cause I was --

00:00:33,835 --> 00:00:35,338
I was diagnosed with skin cancer
  at 26.

00:00:35,338 --> 00:00:37,777
[ voice breaking ] I know
  I am just starting, but...

00:00:37,777 --> 00:00:39,380
This is my passion.

00:00:39,380 --> 00:00:42,218
I haven't have any food
  for eight days.

00:00:42,218 --> 00:00:44,490
You are so full of crap!
  I don't get you.

00:00:44,490 --> 00:00:45,726
CUBAN:
  You're the one who told us

00:00:45,726 --> 00:00:46,962
you know your company
  inside and out.

00:00:46,962 --> 00:00:48,999
We have sold
  a half a million of these.

00:00:48,999 --> 00:00:50,536
Wow!
  what?!

00:00:50,536 --> 00:00:52,540
NARRATOR:
  If the sharks hear a great idea,

00:00:52,540 --> 00:00:55,045
they're ready to invest
  using their own money.

00:00:55,045 --> 00:00:56,281
I want to give you
  an opportunity.

00:00:56,281 --> 00:00:58,118
NARRATOR: And they're willing
  to fight each other

00:00:58,118 --> 00:00:59,922
for a piece of the action.

00:00:59,922 --> 00:01:01,391
O'LEARY:
  I'll give you $75,000.

00:01:01,391 --> 00:01:03,328
I want a royalty of 7%.

00:01:03,328 --> 00:01:05,232
I say I give you the $150,000,

00:01:05,232 --> 00:01:07,269
and we tell this bozo
  to take a walk.

00:01:07,269 --> 00:01:08,305
Ohh!

00:01:09,474 --> 00:01:10,910
NARRATOR:
  Who are the sharks?

00:01:12,313 --> 00:01:15,152
They're self-made millionaire
  and billionaire investors

00:01:15,152 --> 00:01:17,658
who are entrepreneurs
  themselves.

00:01:17,658 --> 00:01:20,062
Kevin o'Leary
  is a venture capitalist

00:01:20,062 --> 00:01:22,768
who turned a $10,000 loan

00:01:22,768 --> 00:01:27,411
into a software business
  worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:27,411 --> 00:01:29,848
Daymond John is
  a fashion and branding expert

00:01:29,848 --> 00:01:31,887
who grew
  his homemade clothing line

00:01:31,887 --> 00:01:35,160
into the globally recognized
  fashion brand Fubu,

00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:38,566
with over $6 billion
  in retail sales to date.

00:01:38,566 --> 00:01:41,740
Robert Herjavec, the son
  of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:41,740 --> 00:01:44,411
is now a technology mogul

00:01:44,411 --> 00:01:48,954
who sold his first internet
  companies for over $350 million.

00:01:48,954 --> 00:01:51,325
Lori Greiner, the queen of QVC,

00:01:51,325 --> 00:01:55,367
holds over 100 patents and
  has launched over 300 products,

00:01:55,367 --> 00:01:58,640
grossing over a half a billion
  dollars in retail sales.

00:01:58,640 --> 00:02:00,878
And Mark Cuban,

00:02:00,878 --> 00:02:03,684
notorious billionaire
  entrepreneur, tech guru,

00:02:03,684 --> 00:02:07,692
and the outspoken owner
  of the NBA's Dallas mavericks.

00:02:15,441 --> 00:02:18,313
[ birds chirping ]

00:02:18,313 --> 00:02:21,721
We have to put on our sunscreen.
  we got to be sun-safe.

00:02:21,721 --> 00:02:23,925
I'm Betsy Johnson. I live
  in prairie village, Kansas,

00:02:23,925 --> 00:02:25,729
with my amazing husband, Matt,
  and my adorable son, Andy.

00:02:25,729 --> 00:02:29,135
Do you want to go outside?
  Time for a walk!

00:02:29,135 --> 00:02:31,006
I was diagnosed with skin cancer
  at 26.

00:02:31,006 --> 00:02:32,910
And it was actually
  one of the scariest things

00:02:32,910 --> 00:02:33,945
that ever happened to me.

00:02:33,945 --> 00:02:35,549
I quickly learned
  that one bad sunburn

00:02:35,549 --> 00:02:38,054
can really affect people
  for the rest of their lives.

00:02:38,054 --> 00:02:41,160
So I decided that I wanted
  to start a business

00:02:41,160 --> 00:02:42,997
to keep everybody sun-safe.

00:02:43,999 --> 00:02:45,569
JOHNSON: Hey, Ber!
  hi, Bets! How's it going?

00:02:47,941 --> 00:02:50,345
It can be a bit of a struggle,
  because he lives in Pittsburgh.

00:02:50,345 --> 00:02:52,516
Thankfully, for the internet,
  it makes it possible

00:02:52,516 --> 00:02:54,253
for Berry and I
  to be in the same room.

00:02:54,253 --> 00:02:56,123
I know
  that we're gonna be big.

00:02:56,123 --> 00:02:58,228
Berry has reservations
  about coming on "Shark Tank,"

00:02:58,228 --> 00:02:59,931
because he thinks
  we can do it on our own

00:02:59,931 --> 00:03:01,535
without giving up
  any of our company.

00:03:01,535 --> 00:03:03,204
But I feel
  we don't have the experience

00:03:03,204 --> 00:03:05,008
and the business connections
  like the sharks.

00:03:05,008 --> 00:03:07,145
If we don't get a deal
  with the sharks,

00:03:07,145 --> 00:03:08,649
I don't think
  our business can grow as big

00:03:08,649 --> 00:03:10,686
as it actually could be.

00:03:25,616 --> 00:03:27,688
Hi, sharks. I'm Betsy Johnson.

00:03:27,688 --> 00:03:29,291
And I'm Berry wanless.

00:03:29,291 --> 00:03:31,094
BOTH: And we are the siblings
  behind Swimzip...

00:03:31,094 --> 00:03:32,731
A sun-protective
  swimwear line.

00:03:32,731 --> 00:03:36,873
WANLESS: We're seeking $60,000
  for a 5% stake in Swimzip.

00:03:36,873 --> 00:03:39,345
JOHNSON: As parents,
  we want to keep our babies safe

00:03:39,345 --> 00:03:42,150
and protected
  from the sun's harmful rays.

00:03:42,150 --> 00:03:46,359
No matter how diligently
  we apply and reapply sunscreen,

00:03:46,359 --> 00:03:48,697
we are still subjecting
  our children's skin

00:03:48,697 --> 00:03:51,869
to the harsh sun and
  potentially painful sunburns.

00:03:51,869 --> 00:03:54,775
Taking kids to the pool
  and beach should be fun,

00:03:54,775 --> 00:03:57,214
but with all the screaming
  and fighting and fussing,

00:03:57,214 --> 00:04:00,822
traditional sun-protective
  methods are such a chore.

00:04:00,822 --> 00:04:02,157
There has to be
  a better way.

00:04:02,157 --> 00:04:03,828
You got it!
  there has to be
  a better way.

00:04:03,828 --> 00:04:07,334
Let us introduce you
  to the super-stylish

00:04:07,334 --> 00:04:08,838
U.V.-protective swimwear line

00:04:08,838 --> 00:04:12,379
that keeps kids sun-safe
  and parents sane.

00:04:12,379 --> 00:04:14,115
Swimzip features
  our signature full-length zipper

00:04:14,115 --> 00:04:15,351
down the front,

00:04:15,351 --> 00:04:17,989
so it's extremely easy
  to put on and take off.

00:04:17,989 --> 00:04:19,993
And both our tops
  and our bottoms

00:04:19,993 --> 00:04:25,304
block 98% of U.V.A.
  and U.V.B. cancer-causing rays.

00:04:25,304 --> 00:04:28,244
In fact, Swimzip's
  sun-protective swimwear

00:04:28,244 --> 00:04:30,381
is so simple to put on,

00:04:30,381 --> 00:04:32,987
kids can literally
  do it themselves.

00:04:32,987 --> 00:04:35,558
Just one quick zip
  leads to a day

00:04:35,558 --> 00:04:38,230
full of
  easy sun protection.
  wow!
  good job!

00:04:38,230 --> 00:04:40,869
All right, sharks,
  who wants to zip up this deal?

00:04:40,869 --> 00:04:43,742
Are you designing and
  manufacturing all of this today?

00:04:43,742 --> 00:04:45,579
Yep. I do
  all the designs myself.

00:04:45,579 --> 00:04:46,881
We create all the prints.

00:04:46,881 --> 00:04:48,952
We work directly
  with the manufacturer.

00:04:48,952 --> 00:04:50,322
It's very stylish.
  I love the little stuff.

00:04:50,322 --> 00:04:52,226
Really quick,
  we got samples for you, so...

00:04:52,226 --> 00:04:53,562
GREINER:
  oh, great. Great.

00:04:53,562 --> 00:04:54,397
Totally.

00:04:54,397 --> 00:04:56,434
Yeah.
  thanks.

00:04:56,434 --> 00:04:57,670
GREINER:
  thank you.

00:04:57,670 --> 00:04:59,273
JOHN: Thank you.

00:04:59,273 --> 00:05:00,709
Is this an adult-size?

00:05:00,709 --> 00:05:02,146
No. It's actually
  the kid-size.

00:05:02,146 --> 00:05:03,348
Thanks, bud.

00:05:03,348 --> 00:05:04,717
Our swimsuits
  actually come as sets,

00:05:04,717 --> 00:05:06,421
so you get
  both a top and a bottom

00:05:06,421 --> 00:05:08,125
when you purchase
  our product.

00:05:08,125 --> 00:05:09,728
Wave bye!
  say thanks!

00:05:09,728 --> 00:05:10,864
HERJAVEC:
  See you guys!
  Bye, guys!

00:05:14,605 --> 00:05:15,874
What are your sales?

00:05:15,874 --> 00:05:17,376
We sold $225,000
  this year.

00:05:17,376 --> 00:05:18,646
HERJAVEC:
  Was that your first year?

00:05:18,646 --> 00:05:20,149
That's our third year
  in business.

00:05:20,149 --> 00:05:22,754
Third year. What were the sales
  the second year?

00:05:22,754 --> 00:05:26,127
The second year, $18,000,
  so we've grown 1,100%.

00:05:26,127 --> 00:05:27,531
How are you selling them?

00:05:27,531 --> 00:05:29,635
We sell on Amazon.
  We sell on our website.

00:05:29,635 --> 00:05:31,172
We also sell
  on the target website.

00:05:31,172 --> 00:05:33,109
We also sell
  in high-end hotels.

00:05:33,109 --> 00:05:35,113
JOHN: You're selling
  to the independent stores?

00:05:35,113 --> 00:05:37,050
Yeah.
  It's fairly small, right?

00:05:37,050 --> 00:05:38,452
It is fairly small
  right now.

00:05:38,452 --> 00:05:41,725
We have stores that sell
  in Japan, Germany, Guam.

00:05:41,725 --> 00:05:43,830
What are you
  making it for?

00:05:43,830 --> 00:05:45,066
$5 to $7.

00:05:45,066 --> 00:05:47,537
O'LEARY:
  What were your profits?
  $100,000.

00:05:47,537 --> 00:05:48,941
But you didn't pay yourselves
  anything, right?

00:05:48,941 --> 00:05:50,410
We currently
  don't take a salary.

00:05:50,410 --> 00:05:52,447
O'LEARY:
  So, you've basically told me
  it's worth $1.2 million.

00:05:52,447 --> 00:05:55,220
You're offering me 5%
  for $60,000, right?

00:05:55,220 --> 00:05:58,192
Mm-hmm.
  You're making $100,000
  without paying yourselves.

00:05:58,192 --> 00:06:00,029
If you each paid yourself
  $50,000,

00:06:00,029 --> 00:06:02,268
which is not unreasonable,
  you make nothing.

00:06:02,268 --> 00:06:03,437
This year, yes.

00:06:04,939 --> 00:06:07,979
Is there anything unique about
  the materials that you're using?

00:06:07,979 --> 00:06:09,949
Nope.
  It's swimsuit material.

00:06:11,253 --> 00:06:13,557
HERJAVEC:
  the material is not unique.

00:06:13,557 --> 00:06:16,596
What makes you unique
  is the fact that you have

00:06:16,596 --> 00:06:19,569
that same material
  with a zipper up the front.

00:06:19,569 --> 00:06:20,604
That's it.

00:06:20,604 --> 00:06:21,974
No.
  Well, that's part of it.

00:06:21,974 --> 00:06:23,878
What really sets it apart
  are our designs.

00:06:23,878 --> 00:06:26,316
Betsy designs
  all of these suits herself.

00:06:26,316 --> 00:06:29,222
But where we really come in
  is that our price point

00:06:29,222 --> 00:06:31,259
is $15 wholesale,
  top and bottom.

00:06:31,259 --> 00:06:35,100
The people who we're
  competing with are $45 to $60.

00:06:35,100 --> 00:06:36,537
Without a zipper.

00:06:36,537 --> 00:06:38,574
We're trying to get at what
  this business is really worth.

00:06:38,574 --> 00:06:41,480
I think because you've
  established some market share

00:06:41,480 --> 00:06:43,751
and you've proven you can
  design it -- I don't know --

00:06:43,751 --> 00:06:45,956
I'd put a value on it
  of half a million bucks, maybe,

00:06:45,956 --> 00:06:48,728
but it's not worth
  $1.2 million.

00:06:48,728 --> 00:06:52,602
Let's ask our Fubu
  retail clothing guy.

00:06:52,602 --> 00:06:54,273
Can I set this up myself
  for $500,000?

00:06:54,273 --> 00:06:55,810
Yes.

00:06:55,810 --> 00:06:58,414
So, what do
  I need you for?

00:06:59,818 --> 00:07:01,755
I look at my money
  as gasoline.

00:07:01,755 --> 00:07:03,525
I want to pour it
  on something

00:07:03,525 --> 00:07:05,663
that I already understand
  how it works.

00:07:05,663 --> 00:07:08,602
I just add money. I make
  more money. That's what I love.

00:07:08,602 --> 00:07:12,777
There's no place
  for me to pour my money into.

00:07:12,777 --> 00:07:15,716
I don't see it here.

00:07:15,716 --> 00:07:17,018
I'm out.

00:07:18,522 --> 00:07:21,395
We are
  on the target website,

00:07:21,395 --> 00:07:23,432
and we actually have
  an exclusive line for them.

00:07:23,432 --> 00:07:25,269
They have not taken you
  into the stores yet?

00:07:25,269 --> 00:07:27,407
No. We're trying to work
  right now to do a test
  in the Southern stores.

00:07:27,407 --> 00:07:28,977
JOHN:
  you don't want to do that.

00:07:30,446 --> 00:07:31,515
Why not?

00:07:31,515 --> 00:07:34,722
The big guys and girls
  can crush you

00:07:34,722 --> 00:07:36,859
with just
  one set of returns.

00:07:36,859 --> 00:07:38,095
Yeah.

00:07:38,095 --> 00:07:40,065
Their margins
  are so, so small.

00:07:40,065 --> 00:07:42,504
You want to stay where you are,
  with the boutiques.

00:07:42,504 --> 00:07:45,410
But that's
  part of the problem here.

00:07:45,410 --> 00:07:47,881
You're a little green
  in understanding all this.

00:07:47,881 --> 00:07:49,885
Now, I have to
  take my hat off to you.

00:07:49,885 --> 00:07:51,856
You made it past
  the hardest point --

00:07:51,856 --> 00:07:54,128
to show proof of concept.
  well -- yeah.

00:07:54,128 --> 00:07:55,597
But there's bad stuff
  coming.

00:07:55,597 --> 00:07:59,271
It's a tough one for me, because
  I see the growth potential here.

00:08:03,480 --> 00:08:06,586
It's just a little too early
  for me, so I'm out.

00:08:09,525 --> 00:08:11,195
JOHNSON:
  I started this company

00:08:11,195 --> 00:08:13,767
'cause I was diagnosed
  with skin cancer at 26.

00:08:13,767 --> 00:08:16,339
[ voice breaking ]
  and, you know...

00:08:16,339 --> 00:08:18,811
I had insurance
  and a paycheck...

00:08:18,811 --> 00:08:20,080
And quit.

00:08:20,080 --> 00:08:23,854
I decided to try to take
  this on, and this is my passion.

00:08:23,854 --> 00:08:26,460
Like, I know this company
  and sun protection

00:08:26,460 --> 00:08:27,962
is the wave of the future,

00:08:27,962 --> 00:08:29,699
and we're starting
  with swimwear.

00:08:29,699 --> 00:08:31,837
And, you know,
  I still have a lot to learn.

00:08:33,574 --> 00:08:35,778
But I'm a fighter,
  and I will build this brand,

00:08:35,778 --> 00:08:37,148
and I will build this swimwear

00:08:37,148 --> 00:08:40,187
to be the best swimwear line
  that kids can have.

00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:42,492
I'm a mommy on a mission.

00:08:42,492 --> 00:08:47,335
My 1-year-old is just --
  he is my world.

00:08:47,335 --> 00:08:48,738
And we go to the park,

00:08:48,738 --> 00:08:51,611
and he wears his Swimzips,
  because I can't find anything.

00:08:51,611 --> 00:08:54,215
I am pushing this product.

00:08:54,215 --> 00:08:58,224
I know I am just starting,
  and I have made mistakes,

00:08:58,224 --> 00:09:00,662
but we will bring this company
  to something huge.

00:09:00,662 --> 00:09:03,368
And, you know, I just --
  i-i don't think you understand.

00:09:03,368 --> 00:09:05,372
We're just at the tip
  of the iceberg here.

00:09:07,276 --> 00:09:12,086
$225,000 sales is nothing
  to laugh at by -- by any means.

00:09:12,086 --> 00:09:14,156
And I think Daymond's right --
  you are green.

00:09:14,156 --> 00:09:16,695
But, you know, frankly,
  all of us up here,

00:09:16,695 --> 00:09:19,968
if we knew the things we should
  be afraid of in business,

00:09:19,968 --> 00:09:21,505
we may have never started.

00:09:21,505 --> 00:09:22,941
[ laughs ]
  Right?

00:09:22,941 --> 00:09:24,310
Yeah, that's true.

00:09:24,310 --> 00:09:26,615
And what is really apparent
  about you and you, Berry,

00:09:26,615 --> 00:09:27,784
is that, you know,

00:09:27,784 --> 00:09:31,425
the best way to get over
  doubt and inexperience

00:09:31,425 --> 00:09:32,861
is simply action.

00:09:34,431 --> 00:09:36,902
I'm just struggling with,
  how do you go

00:09:36,902 --> 00:09:41,645
from a little boutique business
  to millions of dollars?

00:09:41,645 --> 00:09:42,982
I don't have the answer.

00:09:42,982 --> 00:09:44,986
And because
  I don't see the answer,

00:09:44,986 --> 00:09:46,823
I'm not gonna give you
  my money today.

00:09:46,823 --> 00:09:47,825
I'm out.

00:09:53,402 --> 00:09:55,674
Betsy, you're a beast.

00:09:55,674 --> 00:09:57,845
Thanks.
  and that's
  an enormous compliment.

00:09:57,845 --> 00:09:59,582
Berry, you're there to help her,
  and that's a great thing.

00:09:59,582 --> 00:10:01,686
But you're still
  a family business.

00:10:01,686 --> 00:10:04,124
And family businesses aren't
  to the point of their life cycle

00:10:04,124 --> 00:10:05,828
where they can just explode.

00:10:05,828 --> 00:10:07,965
You haven't even broken out

00:10:07,965 --> 00:10:10,437
of the "I'm hiring my friends
  and family" mode yet.

00:10:10,437 --> 00:10:12,208
Then you get to 10 employees
  or 15 employees.

00:10:12,208 --> 00:10:14,011
Then you have to manage
  those employees, right?

00:10:14,011 --> 00:10:16,683
It's just a huge step.
  and until you get to that step,

00:10:16,683 --> 00:10:18,888
it's much more difficult
  to be ignited

00:10:18,888 --> 00:10:20,758
and to have
  that inflection point.

00:10:20,758 --> 00:10:22,461
And honestly,
  I learned a lot of lessons

00:10:22,461 --> 00:10:24,700
from the 30 companies
  I've invested in on "Shark Tank"

00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:25,969
that proved that point to me.

00:10:25,969 --> 00:10:27,571
Well, I want
  a strategic investor.

00:10:27,571 --> 00:10:29,308
I don't want to be
  a family business.

00:10:29,308 --> 00:10:32,616
Like I said, I want this
  out there, and I need the help.

00:10:32,616 --> 00:10:33,985
I'm out.

00:10:38,861 --> 00:10:41,767
Okay, we have one shark left.
  Lori?

00:10:41,767 --> 00:10:45,942
You know, I was a one-man band
  for five years.

00:10:45,942 --> 00:10:49,016
I had passion and drive
