  you make no money!

00:13:18,017 --> 00:13:19,855
You have no paycheck.

00:13:20,923 --> 00:13:22,359
We need this deal.

00:13:22,359 --> 00:13:24,530
JOHN: Berry,
  why aren't you saying much?

00:13:24,530 --> 00:13:26,167
Why are you so hesitant?

00:13:26,167 --> 00:13:30,075
'cause I think I'm the reason
  that she's not saying yes.

00:13:30,075 --> 00:13:31,879
Why? Why not?
  why isn't she
  saying yes?

00:13:31,879 --> 00:13:33,214
Because I believe
  in our company.

00:13:33,214 --> 00:13:35,018
I think we are gonna be
  a $5 million company.

00:13:35,018 --> 00:13:37,457
And if we're giving someone
  this 20% stake right now,

00:13:37,457 --> 00:13:39,895
it's a huge, huge part
  of our business.

00:13:39,895 --> 00:13:42,967
I don't want to push you
  into anything.

00:13:42,967 --> 00:13:45,907
If you're not comfortable
  with this deal, don't take it.

00:13:45,907 --> 00:13:50,249
I'm taking a chance on you
  because I believed in you.

00:13:51,718 --> 00:13:53,255
A bigger chance, now,
  than you thought.

00:13:53,255 --> 00:13:56,528
This is about money.
  make a decision.

00:13:56,528 --> 00:13:58,532
What do you want to do?

00:14:02,173 --> 00:14:03,910
Let's try it.

00:14:03,910 --> 00:14:04,912
Okay.

00:14:04,912 --> 00:14:07,183
All right.
  Lori, you have a deal!

00:14:07,183 --> 00:14:09,054
Oh. All right. Good.

00:14:09,054 --> 00:14:10,490
[ laughs ]
  [ sighs ]

00:14:10,490 --> 00:14:13,028
Berry, you have to get
  on the train.
  let's do this!

00:14:13,028 --> 00:14:15,167
I'm on the train.
  all right.
  good. Good.

00:14:16,135 --> 00:14:18,406
Bye. Thank you.
  HERJAVEC:
  Good luck, guys.

00:14:18,406 --> 00:14:19,442
Berry, ask for a paycheck.

00:14:19,442 --> 00:14:23,016
We got it! Yes!

00:14:23,016 --> 00:14:24,987
Lori,
  we are gonna do this!

00:14:24,987 --> 00:14:27,057
WANLESS: I think I was
  a little hesitant at first

00:14:27,057 --> 00:14:29,061
because we do
  value our company a lot

00:14:29,061 --> 00:14:31,266
and we do anticipate
  huge sales.

00:14:31,266 --> 00:14:33,671
But I do think,
  at the end of the day,
  it was the right deal

00:14:33,671 --> 00:14:35,875
and that Lori's gonna be
  fantastic, a fantastic partner.

00:14:35,875 --> 00:14:37,278
We're really excited
  about that.

00:14:41,954 --> 00:14:43,256
NARRATOR: In season 2,

00:14:43,256 --> 00:14:45,561
Kimberly Nelson made a deal
  with Barbara Corcoran

00:14:45,561 --> 00:14:48,367
for her homemade-cake business,
  Daisy Cakes.

00:14:48,367 --> 00:14:49,736
What do you think?
  Do we have a deal?

00:14:49,736 --> 00:14:50,805
Of course.

00:14:50,805 --> 00:14:51,674
Whew!

00:14:51,674 --> 00:14:53,811
Let's see what she's doing now.

00:14:53,811 --> 00:14:57,118
Daisy Cakes has gone through
  some major changes

00:14:57,118 --> 00:14:58,621
since my last update.

00:14:58,621 --> 00:15:01,861
On my last update, we moved
  all the baking out of state

00:15:01,861 --> 00:15:03,564
to a large-production bakery.

00:15:03,564 --> 00:15:06,036
It seemed like the only way
  to meet the demand

00:15:06,036 --> 00:15:08,040
and keep my customers happy.

00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:11,180
For a few months,
  everything was good.

00:15:11,180 --> 00:15:14,821
And then things just started
  to spiral downward.

00:15:14,821 --> 00:15:17,860
We made a couple
  of really poor hiring decisions,

00:15:17,860 --> 00:15:20,733
and the quality of the cakes
  was so bad,

00:15:20,733 --> 00:15:24,540
we lost nearly $150,000
  in bad product.

00:15:24,540 --> 00:15:25,976
The worst part is,

00:15:25,976 --> 00:15:29,283
that damaged our reputation
  with our most loyal customers.

00:15:29,283 --> 00:15:31,254
We take a lot of pride

00:15:31,254 --> 00:15:34,060
in these Daisy Cakes
  being made the right way.

00:15:34,060 --> 00:15:36,664
So, with some really good
  words of advice from Barbara,

00:15:36,664 --> 00:15:40,272
we decided to bring
  the Daisy Cakes baking back here

00:15:40,272 --> 00:15:42,543
to Pauline, South Carolina,
  where it started.

00:15:42,543 --> 00:15:44,514
So, how are y'all doing
  on these? You got enough?

00:15:44,514 --> 00:15:45,717
We're back to basics here,

00:15:45,717 --> 00:15:48,188
and I've hired
  a great team of employees.

00:15:48,188 --> 00:15:49,525
And I learned
  a really big lesson --

00:15:49,525 --> 00:15:51,227
that's that nobody's gonna make
  a Daisy cake

00:15:51,227 --> 00:15:53,064
the way my mom and I
  are gonna make a Daisy cake.

00:15:53,064 --> 00:15:55,703
CORCORAN: I knew I'd be
  finding you hard at work!

00:15:55,703 --> 00:15:57,808
Come on!
  show me the operation!
  oh, my God!

00:15:57,808 --> 00:16:00,112
Barbara has been
  a tremendous support,

00:16:00,112 --> 00:16:03,586
and her guidance has been just
  what we needed for Daisy Cakes.

00:16:03,586 --> 00:16:05,256
Our projected sales
  for Daisy Cakes

00:16:05,256 --> 00:16:08,496
over the next year
  should be close to $3 million.

00:16:08,496 --> 00:16:10,600
Let me tell you something.
  we're just getting started.

00:16:10,600 --> 00:16:12,070
CORCORAN:
  When you're growing a business,

00:16:12,070 --> 00:16:14,742
it's a series of mistakes that
  you have to learn to overcome.

00:16:14,742 --> 00:16:18,049
Kim has the magic ingredient
  of every great entrepreneur.

00:16:18,049 --> 00:16:20,588
When she gets hit,
  she pops right back up.

00:16:20,588 --> 00:16:23,359
And that's why Kim is succeeding
  again at Daisy Cakes.

00:16:23,359 --> 00:16:25,230
NELSON: Just because
  you get a deal on "Shark Tank"

00:16:25,230 --> 00:16:27,802
doesn't mean
  it's going to be an easy road.

00:16:27,802 --> 00:16:29,973
But with Barbara by my side,

00:16:29,973 --> 00:16:32,512
I know the future
  for Daisy Cakes has no limits.

00:16:41,730 --> 00:16:44,335
NARRATOR: Next into the tank
  is an accomplished entrepreneur

00:16:44,335 --> 00:16:48,510
from San Diego, California,
  with a simple way to stay fit.

00:16:52,485 --> 00:16:53,788
Hello, sharks.

00:16:53,788 --> 00:16:57,729
My name is Phil Black,
  and my company is Fitdeck.

00:16:57,729 --> 00:17:00,702
And I'm seeking $300,000

00:17:00,702 --> 00:17:04,343
in exchange
  for 20% of the company.

00:17:04,343 --> 00:17:08,284
Fitdeck is a custom deck
  of fitness playing cards

00:17:08,284 --> 00:17:13,026
that makes exercise more simple,
  convenient, and fun.

00:17:13,026 --> 00:17:15,298
Each card has an illustration

00:17:15,298 --> 00:17:18,004
and instructions
  on how to perform the exercise.

00:17:18,004 --> 00:17:21,577
So all you need to do
  is shuffle, deal, and go.

00:17:21,577 --> 00:17:22,880
Can we see a package?

00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:23,882
Sure.

00:17:23,882 --> 00:17:25,385
And where are you
  selling them?

00:17:25,385 --> 00:17:28,057
Primarily from our website,
  direct to consumer.

00:17:28,057 --> 00:17:29,493
That's about 75%
  of our business.

00:17:29,493 --> 00:17:30,896
So, why don't you take
  Fitdeck body weight?

00:17:30,896 --> 00:17:32,867
HERJAVEC: Thank you.

00:17:32,867 --> 00:17:34,103
This is cross training,
  Daymond,

00:17:34,103 --> 00:17:35,473
thank you.
  our equivalent to crossfit.

00:17:35,473 --> 00:17:36,608
Thank you.

00:17:36,608 --> 00:17:39,013
And, of course, mark --
  Fitdeck basketball.

00:17:39,013 --> 00:17:40,616
Appreciate that.

00:17:40,616 --> 00:17:42,854
So, sharks,
  who's ready to go all-in?

00:17:42,854 --> 00:17:44,491
HERJAVEC: Okay,
  walk me through a single unit.

00:17:44,491 --> 00:17:46,695
What do you sell it for?
  what does it cost to make?

00:17:46,695 --> 00:17:48,298
That sells for $14.95
  on our website.

00:17:48,298 --> 00:17:49,467
It costs about $2 to make.

00:17:49,467 --> 00:17:51,872
Are you selling
  a lot of these cards right now?

00:17:51,872 --> 00:17:54,744
We have sold a half a million
  of these Fitdecks.

00:17:54,744 --> 00:17:56,715
Wow!
  what?!
  in how long
  a period of time?

00:17:56,715 --> 00:17:58,953
That's been
  over the last seven years or so.

00:17:58,953 --> 00:18:02,293
Ohh.
  the majority of those have been
  in the last four years or so.

00:18:02,293 --> 00:18:03,797
Well, how many
  did you sell last year?

00:18:03,797 --> 00:18:05,801
Last year,
  we sold 55,000.

00:18:05,801 --> 00:18:07,771
So, how many dollars
  is that?

00:18:07,771 --> 00:18:09,407
Last year, $640,000.

00:18:09,407 --> 00:18:12,548
Very impressive.
  what was your profit?

00:18:12,548 --> 00:18:13,917
Last year,
  the profit was a break-even.

00:18:13,917 --> 00:18:16,422
Why? How could you
  only break even?

00:18:16,422 --> 00:18:17,958
HERJAVEC:
  there's something missing.

00:18:17,958 --> 00:18:19,495
You got to be making
  a ton of money.

00:18:19,495 --> 00:18:22,267
Or you got screwed
  somewhere along the line.

00:18:22,267 --> 00:18:23,636
Well, last year
  was an anomaly.

00:18:23,636 --> 00:18:26,342
The prior years, we had
  an average of $725,000 in sales

00:18:26,342 --> 00:18:29,181
with an average profit
  of about $120,000.

00:18:29,181 --> 00:18:31,552
So, when your sales dropped,
  your profit was wiped out?

00:18:31,552 --> 00:18:32,856
Correct.

00:18:32,856 --> 00:18:35,227
Okay. So, Phil, here's where
  it doesn't add up for me.

00:18:35,227 --> 00:18:38,901
Let's assume you did $700,000
  two years ago in sales.

00:18:38,901 --> 00:18:42,776
Your cost of goods on that
  would've been $100,000, right?

00:18:42,776 --> 00:18:45,481
That leaves you
  with $600,000.

00:18:45,481 --> 00:18:48,253
You made $100,000.
  that leaves you with $500,000.

00:18:48,253 --> 00:18:52,595
You're spending $500,000
  running a $700,000 company?

00:18:52,595 --> 00:18:54,166
Where's the money going?

00:18:54,166 --> 00:18:56,403
To some r&amp;d --
  we have to create them.

00:18:56,403 --> 00:19:00,011
It's going to making videos.
  we made 100 videos last year.

00:19:00,011 --> 00:19:02,048
We redid the entire website.

00:19:02,048 --> 00:19:04,486
O'LEARY: Phil, my greatest fear
  for this content

00:19:04,486 --> 00:19:06,825
is that when it moves online
  or into an app,

00:19:06,825 --> 00:19:07,927
it's simply free.

00:19:07,927 --> 00:19:10,833
I mean, if you just Google
  these stretches,

00:19:10,833 --> 00:19:13,204
there's a ton of content
  that's there for free.

00:19:13,204 --> 00:19:16,243
Well, the problem with that is
  it's so all over the place

00:19:16,243 --> 00:19:18,047
that if you wanted to do it --
  you could type in

00:19:18,047 --> 00:19:19,750
"stretching exercises
  for a bad hamstring" --

00:19:19,750 --> 00:19:21,821
you're gonna get
  15 million responses.

00:19:21,821 --> 00:19:24,226
And we're breaking it down
  for you to make it very simple.

00:19:24,226 --> 00:19:26,865
What would you like
  the $300,000 for?

00:19:26,865 --> 00:19:28,268
The $300,000 is gonna amount

00:19:28,268 --> 00:19:30,672
to where we think
  the future of the business is.

00:19:30,672 --> 00:19:34,914
So 75% to 80% of that, we feel
  is going on the digital side.

00:19:34,914 --> 00:19:36,517
You're planning
  to sell that app?
  correct.

00:19:36,517 --> 00:19:38,521
CUBAN:
  that's a tough business.
  we've been selling that app

00:19:38,521 --> 00:19:39,958
for the last --
  that's a very tough space.

00:19:39,958 --> 00:19:42,096
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
  you've been selling --
  you have an app?

00:19:42,096 --> 00:19:43,900
We've been selling it
  for about four or five months.

00:19:43,900 --> 00:19:45,737
We're getting
  1,000 downloads a month

00:19:45,737 --> 00:19:47,039
with very little marketing.

00:19:47,039 --> 00:19:48,475
It's all free
  at that point, right?

00:19:48,475 --> 00:19:49,811
No, we sell this
  for $9.99.

00:19:49,811 --> 00:19:52,517
How did you come up with this?
  tell us about your background.

00:19:52,517 --> 00:19:54,454
I was a Navy Seal
  for almost six years.

00:19:54,454 --> 00:19:55,523
CUBAN: You were?
  yes.

00:19:55,523 --> 00:19:57,226
Oh! All right. Thank you.
  good for you.

00:19:57,226 --> 00:19:58,629
Yeah, well, actually,
  the idea for Fitdeck

00:19:58,629 --> 00:20:01,535
was based on a card game that I
  played with my college roommates

00:20:01,535 --> 00:20:02,904
at Yale University.

00:20:02,904 --> 00:20:05,410
And it was a game called "pug,"
  short for "push-up game."

00:20:05,410 --> 00:20:08,115
now, this became
  a campus-wide sensation at Yale.

00:20:08,115 --> 00:20:09,885
You know,
  it made an impression on me.

00:20:09,885 --> 00:20:11,322
I graduated from Yale,

00:20:11,322 --> 00:20:13,693
and I went to one of the biggest
  investment banks in the world

00:20:13,693 --> 00:20:14,761
for about 2 1/2 years.

00:20:14,761 --> 00:20:16,098
Which bank was it, Phil?

00:20:16,098 --> 00:20:17,434
It was Goldman Sachs.
  no kidding.

00:20:17,434 --> 00:20:19,604
Ah!
  oh, my God.
  so, hang on. Hang on.

00:20:19,604 --> 00:20:21,375
You -- you have a degree
  from Yale.

00:20:21,375 --> 00:20:23,680
You were an investment banker,
  and that wasn't enough,

00:20:23,680 --> 00:20:25,516
so then
  you were a Navy Seal.

00:20:25,516 --> 00:20:28,857
I came to my senses after
  the investment banking
  and became a seal.

00:20:28,857 --> 00:20:32,297
So, now you're flying around
  the world doing crazy stuff.
  HERJAVEC:
  okay, and then what happened?

00:20:32,297 --> 00:20:33,834
Well, while I was flying
  around the world,

00:20:33,834 --> 00:20:36,406
we had every fitness product
  and program in the world

00:20:36,406 --> 00:20:38,610
at our fingertips,
  and guess what we played.

00:20:38,610 --> 00:20:40,614
Pug?
  we played the pug game!

00:20:40,614 --> 00:20:43,253
I left, and I went
  to Harvard business school.

00:20:43,253 --> 00:20:44,522
And there --
  [ laughter ]

00:20:44,522 --> 00:20:45,924
HERJAVEC: Okay! Stop!

00:20:45,924 --> 00:20:48,196
All that training --
  you came up with cards?!

00:20:48,196 --> 00:20:49,432
Exactly!

00:20:49,432 --> 00:20:52,071
So, finish the story.

00:20:52,071 --> 00:20:53,673
So, I said,
  "why stop at push-ups?

00:20:53,673 --> 00:20:54,943
"why not take this pug concept

00:20:54,943 --> 00:20:56,914
and create a business
  out of it -- Fitdeck?"

00:20:56,914 --> 00:20:59,720
we can attack all things --
  not just body-weight exercises,

00:20:59,720 --> 00:21:02,726
but yoga, pilates, stretching,
  crossfit, basketball.

